issue.body:
In my test suite I am rolling up a non-trivial number of test cases. I mean a seriously large number of them. This is unavoidable in order to property verify functionality. In prior versions of ``Xunit`` this would work just fine. The roll up itself would take some time, but the tests at least kept running, particularly if I was running these tests in conjunction with others in my test sessions.

However, it seems with the latest version of ``Xunit`` this is breaking down and others among my unit tests are timing out with *inconclusive".

First, is there a way to put a hold on tests until the member data test cases have rolled up?

Second, is there a timeout I can set, disable, etc?

Typically, I am approaching member data test cases something like this:

```C#
private static IEnumerable<object[]> _memberDataTestCases;

public static IEnumerable<object[]> MemberDataTestCases
{
    get
    {
        IEnumerable<object[]> GetAll()
        {
            IEnumerable<object> GetOne(...)
            {
                yield return someArgs;
            }

            yield return GetOne(...).ToArray();
        }

        return _memberDataTestCases ?? (_memberDataTestCases = GetAll().ToArray());
    }
}
```

Depending on the test case, ``GetOne(...)`` or variations thereof can be more or less complex.

In this case I've got some 15,125+ for a given test case.

Like I said, this was not a problem before the most recent ``Xunit`` release. So whatever changed between then and now has had an adverse effect on rolling up a range of tests, test cases, etc, timing out.
